Node.Notes: One of two psalms to mention Solomon in the title (see also ps127).
Tree assumes elision of a verb like "he will have."
Except for this verb, the rest of this verse identical to zc9:10.
Uncertain. Usually wild beast that is a desert dweller, which many take as referring to desert tribes here. Others change text to read "foes" (good parallel with "enemies" that follows).
Lick the dust is an idiom for defeat and submission.
Uncertain. Usually refers to shaking of earthquake, but perhaps less forceful swaying here. Some propose a separate verbal root meaning "to be abundant/thrive."
May they bless themselves in him may mean may they ask God to bless them as he has blessed him (the king) or may they be blessed through him (the king).
